Republican strategy of opposition to Obama's re-election
The Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to fight counterfeiting in elections.
However, in the Brennan Center, the latter is considered a myth, claiming that cases of falsification in the U.S. elections are more rare than cases of deaths from a blast strike.
In addition, Republican lawyers counted only 300 cases of electoral falsification in the United States in ten years.
One thing can be said with certainty: these new trends will have a negative impact on the appearance of voters.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Unlike Canada, the US states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the US.
This is why most state governments have adopted laws since 2009 that complicate the process of registration or voting.
This phenomenon got a new scale after the November 2010 elections that brought the Republicans 675 new seats in 26 states.
As a result, in only one year 2011, 180 bills were adopted restricting voting rights in 41 states.
The new electoral law requires the voter to present a identity card with a photo and proof of the presence of American citizenship.
In addition, these laws shorten the period of early voting, cancell the right to register the voter on the day of declaration of will, and take away the right of vote from the citizens with judgment.
Before the 2006 election, none of the U.S. states required voters to submit a identity card with a photo.
Indiana became the first state to impose such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court confirmed the constitutionality of the law adopted in Indiana in 2008.
The Republican authorities have rushed to spread this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they initiated a bill obliging voters to submit identity certificates with photographs in 34 states.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, American citizens do not have such a universal identity certificate as a medical insurance card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, that is, 21 million people who have reached the required age to vote, don’t have a identity card with a photo issued by the government body of their state.
Moreover, five million new voters in 2012 don’t have such a document.
At the same time, the cost of obtaining the required identity card often exceeds $100.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect youth, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25 percent of African Americans, 15 percent of people earning less than $35,000, 18 percent of citizens aged 65 years and 20 percent of voters aged 18 to 29 years don’t have the required identity card with a photo.
But that’s not all yet.
Students - voters who are believed to vote for candidates from Democrats, in several states are not allowed to use a identity card with a photo issued by their school.
However, the same states allow the members of fishing and hunting clubs, who mostly vote for the Republicans, to use the certificates issued by these clubs for voting.
Until 2004, none of the states required evidence of the presence of American citizenship for voting.
This is the first time that such a requirement has been introduced in Arizona.
Since 2011, more than ten states have adopted laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are obviously aimed at limiting the voting of outgoers from Latin America.
It is estimated that two-thirds of Latin American voters vote for the Democratic Party.
In 2011, the Republican lawmakers also initiated laws abolishing the registration of voters on the day of the vote in eight states.
They also restricted the right of individuals or groups to provide assistance to those who wish to register.
This limitation did not pass without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 election, the voter registration campaign helped put about 10 million citizens into the lists.
At the same time, measures taken since 2009 have led to a 17% decline in the registration of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators have adopted laws in five other states aimed at shortening the period of premature voting.
Thus, during the 2008 general elections in Florida, 33% of the voters voting early were African-Americans, although the latter were only 13% of the total number of voters in the state.
The same happened with those from Latin America.
Representing only 11% of the voters, they accounted for 24% of the citizens who voted early.
Unlike the white, which, forming 76% of the voters, among the voters early voted was only 46%.
Of course, Democrats and their supporters are actively opposing the adoption of laws that restrict the registration of voters.
Several draft laws were promised by governors-democrats.
The action of the most unambiguous laws was suspended by the intervention of the United States Prosecutor General.
This allowed to partially limit the negative consequences.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have adopted laws requiring the presentation of identity certificates with a photo.
However, the new rules that came into force will make it difficult to exercise the voting right in the 2012 elections.
Critics from Democrats condemn the prejudice of the laws that have been adopted, seeing in them an obvious focus on influencing the results of the 2012 elections in key states.
The 2011 Brennan Center report shows that the states that adopted these laws represent 171 out of the 270 votes required in the electoral council to win the presidential election.
It is too early to assert with confidence that these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential elections.
Only one thing is undoubted: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the appearance of voters.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
