Higgs Boson in Details
Last summer, the message that scientists may have managed to discover the Higgs boson caused a real agitation – and not without reason.
It is believed that this boson explains the mass of all the particles in the universe, neither much nor little.
Furthermore, it is the last particle whose existence was predicted within the Standard Model — our best, or, in any case, the "most imperfect" description of nature and behavior of matter — but which was not previously discovered by experience.
But physicists are not yet completely sure that it is the Higgs boson.
We know, without a shadow of doubt, that we are dealing with a truly new particle and that it resembles Higgs' boson predicted by the Standard Model.
Additionally, the new data presented this week at a large physical congress in Kyoto seems to confirm this, although for full confidence some data is not yet available.
Let’s still imagine that it’s about the Higgs boson, as the chances of mistake seem minimal, and let’s see what it means.
There is, in this world, one law completely inevitable, which states that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There is no possibility to overcome this rule, don’t even try too hard, otherwise hurt yourself.
But although the physics of elementary particles is a rather strange world, it turns out that there is also one law of similar nature: the principle of Paul's exclusion, which postulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" consists, in common features, in some of their characteristics.
Based on this, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find good-order citizens, called fermions, who reasonably obey the principle of Paul.
In the other, the bosons, an angry gang of anarchists, who have no respect for anything, at least for that principle, which means that they can calmly be in the same place at the same time.
The Particle Adventure Laboratory of Berkeley reports that these bosons are, in turn, divided into two groups: the mesons that we will not talk about here, and the “particles of force” through which the main forces of nature are spread and to which in some way the Higgs boson applies.
These most bosons should be emphasized, not all such exotic beings as you could think.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, then it is due to one incredibly banal boson: the photon, or the “particle of light,” which is the “curator” of the electromagnetic power.
In fact, when one particle with electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it “breaks” the electromagnetic field in that particular place, like a stone thrown into a pipe.
From this “infraction” a electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared radiation, or ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing but a photon – and therefore one of the bosons of “power carriers.”
More stable field
The same happens with the Higgs boson, with the only difference that in order for this boson to appear, another field, Higgs field, must be "broken".
However, the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, it is necessary to reach very and very high energies, as if it was a frozen grid, the surface of which could be overwhelmed by only a very large stone.
That’s why we need a huge particle accelerator, like the one that is operated in the CERN – the Great Adron Collar, a ring with a diameter of 27 km! – to reach such enormous energies.
Analogue with the electromagnetic field is also useful to explain the ratio between the Higgs boson and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, interact, others do not: a paper sheet, for example, will never hold itself on the refrigerator.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that interact have mass, while others (like photon, by the way) do not have it.
So what can all these studies bring, asks Mrs. Plamondon?
In science, they are used to verify the correctness of the Standard Model (SM), and this also allows physicists to perceive the difference between the results of observations and the forecasts of the SM.
Additionally, some of them are passionate that such a difference may be discovered, since the smallest disagreement can open the door to "new physics" and shut down some hole of the Model.
The latter, to say, still has substantial shortcomings, without offering any explanation for gravity (the!) or for dark matter, which forms about 80% of the universe (the!).
But so far such differences have not been found.
Consequences
The benefit of these studies for the daily life of an average person is harder to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that it is not.
In the early 1960s, the pioneers of the Bell laboratory laser research could not even guess what revolution their work would trigger.
They predicted their applications in science, but not more.
In fact, the already dead physicist Willard Boyle, who worked in the Bell Laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the previous was impulsive) in 1962, said that the laser was initially considered rather as a "laboratory gadget."
Imagine...
In addition, the application can be found for the tools that accompany the research.
For example, the same William Boyle developed a small light sensor during his optical research in 1969.
This sensor, although it was not its original purpose at all, now serves as a "eye" for all digital cameras in the world and has earned the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This, of course, does not mean that the work of the Great Adron Collider will necessarily change our lives, but it only shows, in fact, that everything can be.
