“In the last six months from three to five cakes, cancer patients under the age of 45 have always been busy,” says Dr. Christian Martel concerned.
53% of the patients taken to Victor-Gadbu's shelter come from home, and 47% from the hospital.
Access to palliative care
It is believed that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, i.e. to care that is provided to relieve the suffering of patients who have entered the final stage of their lives, whether it is at home, in the hospital or in the refuge.
And some institutions, such as the Victor-Gadbua Pride and the Society of Palliative Care at the House of the Great Montreal, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is this big gap in Quebec’s healthcare system that causes many doctors – palliative care specialists – to be afraid of a law that legalizes euthanasia and suicide assistance.
Starting from October, a manifesto signed by lights in the field of palliative care, Dr. Balfur Mount and Dr. Bernard Liapuant, is circulating and testifies that they disagree with such initiative.
According to Dr. Christian Martel, Quebec’s healthcare system is not efficient enough to ensure the right to high-quality palliative care before the transition to euthanasia is permitted.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who spent 14 days in the emergency department, in terrible pain, and no one took the necessary measures to relieve them.
I'm afraid that patients want to die only because they don't get adequate care.
At the same time, many oncologists until the last day are trying to save patients despite pessimistic forecasts.
Ellen Richard's hopes of survival were already minimal when she stopped chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I’m ceasing treatment, she replied that she’s sorry that I’m ceasing the fight.
She told me that my days were counted.
There is no full care.
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of the patients who ask for death thank the medical staff for their failure to fulfill their request after the palliative care team relieves their pain.
However, it should be noted that palliative care is not absolutely comprehensive in the fight against pain.
According to Elsey Monroe, director of palliative care at the Society of Palliative Care at the House of Great Montreal, patients are not susceptible to anesthesia in 8% of cases.
At the end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, in which the patient sleeps until the moment of his death, either from time to time, or constantly.
We can’t pretend that we don’t know about these suffering.
More and more patients who are unable to relieve the pain will be able to have access to palliative sedation.
Patients suffering from pain always say the same phrase: “I want to die.”
But it doesn’t necessarily mean “I want me to be euthanasia,” it means “I want me to be easier.”
