He describes bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency", "concurring with the dollar or the euro" and "like the usual currencies."
Bitcoin is different from other types of virtual currencies, as “credits” used to promote in video games that are earned during the game or that can be purchased (and sometimes exchanged).
The social network Facebook also developed a similar system.
But the exchange operations are always controlled and processed by any central body.
In Bitcoin, all nodes of the network are simultaneously accountants, auditors, currency emitters, buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually occurs between two email addresses, like an email.
Only for each new payment the user can choose a different address, thereby providing anonymity.
The information relating to this transaction is signed electronically, using a double-key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is possible to verify that the bitcoin used in the transaction actually exists in a public account book sent throughout the network.
The key step is to register a new transaction in this book.
It passes through the solution of a mathematical task sent to computers, which the soldier, like a temporary central bank, receives the privilege of adding this new line.
This is about the file hashing phase, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a digital signature, short and unique.
Computers will "take" a new transaction and add a number to it before "hacking" everything together.
The goal is to find a number that will give a unique digital signature (many zero at the beginning).
Once this number is found, other nodes easily check that it is right.
The transaction is thus uninterruptly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification will change the digital signature.
If for the purpose of fraud the user would like to pay twice the same topic with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), only one of these two transactions would be confirmed by the network - and the other would remain unconfirmed, as they have different electronic signatures.
The computer that solves the task receives 50 bitcoins.
In order to avoid inflation, the prize is regularly divided by half, probably by the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoin in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divided to one hundred million, which leaves another reserve.
The complexity of the task also increases with the increase in the computing capacity.
The life of the network has already suffered rises and falls.
The sites that provide Bitcoin services were attacked, and Bitcoin were stolen from the reserves.
“The fault used does not affect the protocol itself,” says Pierre Nouza, who recently launched Paymium, a real-time payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this disadvantage.
Big players, such as Wikipedia, refuse to accept donations of this kind.
Others, such as the WordPress blog platform, allow them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the account and found that 80% of Bitcoin is not in turnover.
“Gigant sales” were announced in November.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works at Coinabul, which is engaged in converting bitcoin into gold.
Pierre Nuaza, another author of the currency benefits, strongly believes in the potential of this technology as an operating network.
His system, Paytunia, is the equivalent of a credit card (in real money) or non-contact payment via a mobile phone, but it uses Bitcoin to verify transactions that thus comes out cheaper.
The owner better controls his personal data and can thus be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for entrepreneurs who do not need to install new devices or software.
It’s only enough to indicate the address that can be “photographed and recognized” by phone, says Pierre Nuaza, confirming that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general trend of revision of hierarchical systems in favour of more horizontal.
“Before Bitcoin is approved, it will take a while, but 2013 can be a turning point,” he predicts.
By the way, the ECB in its report proposes to review the various risks that are considered to be increased today, if the system succeeds.
