Poland and space.
Last week, at the meeting of ministers of the European Space Agency, Poland was adopted as the twenty-member of the European Space Agency as the second country in the country of the former Eastern Block (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of the ECA on September 12, 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with the ECA in 1994 and during the subsequent years participated actively in a number of agency projects.
But the journey to the space of Poland began much earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in flights to space, but this was not always understood.
I will remember, for example, the lecture of A. Sternfeld, who on December 6, 1933 presented in the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory the idea of his innovative work "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
The ideas of a young engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, after a few years, Sternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934 in France, Sternfeld won the Robert Essno-Peltry and André Luis Hirsch Prize for "Introduction to Cosmonautics."
Dr. Jan Gadomsky (1899 - 1966), which was mentioned above, later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a number of books dedicated to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky became a world-famous promoter of cosmonautics, and his contribution was appreciated including by the fact that one of the craters on the reverse side of the moon was named in his honor.
In 1925 in Poland was built a railway drain equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remained unknown, as well as the details of the project.
It is not even clear whether a missile had to be used to dismantle or freeze the carriage.
Information about this dressing is known only from the press of that time.
Since 1933, the Polish artillery began to think about missile shells.
The investigation was carried out by the Department of Arms Engineering in cooperation with professors Mechislav Wolfke and Gustav Moczicki.
The preserved materials show that the research has reached the stage of practical testing.
But with the arrival of the German troops the work was interrupted.
In 1937, the idea of a photovoltaic fighter missile appeared in the specialized press, which was proposed by the engineer Rogozinsky, and the following year the work "Air torpedo missile and aviation missile-bomb" was published by the author of Lelyva-Kzivoblatsky.
Both projects were designed for military use of missile engines.
Before the war, all the projects of military use of missile equipment were carried out by the Timczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy, which coordinated all the work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of its activity the work ended due to the beginning of the war.
The following scientific work, dedicated to cosmonautics, appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time about society is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the magazine "Problems", in which four volume articles on astronomy are published.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovich proposed to organize a society that will engage in cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already moving, and it was clear that space research was a prospective industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Society of Astronautics (POA) tried to join the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951) and in the autumn of the POA became its actual member.
And next year, the first chairman of the POA Kazimej Zarankević (1902 - 1959) became the deputy chairman of the International Federation of Astronomy.
He remained in this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the POA has made a significant contribution to the development of the very successful meteorological missile RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish missile to perform scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957, and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
The missile, capable of overcoming a distance of 1800 m, was about 80 cm long, and its weight was less than 5 kg.
The improved version of the RM-1A was subsequently built, and in the summer of 1959 the two-stage RM-2 missile was tested in the Bledow Desert.
This missile was about 1.4 m long, and its weight was about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the missile was already able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 could overcome 14.5 km, and its task was to monitor the high wind.
But in 1962 further development was stopped.
The inheritance of the first RM-type missiles was the Meteor-1 missile developed between 1962 and 1965.
The missile was conceived as a two-step, its total length was 510 cm, and the initial weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (defined as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed by the size of the camera for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A missile had a space of 0.4 liters, the Meteor-1B 0.34 liters, and the Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum flight distance for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 was developed at the Aviation Institute, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 missile with a starting weight of 380 kg was able to carry a useful cargo of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Then the versions of Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning that Poland joined the Cospar (Committee for Space Studies) in 1960 and the establishment of the Cospar National Committee two years later.
In addition, as part of the Intercosmos program, Poland participated in space studies on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslav Germanhevsky became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
