Sabo: “Germans should play a more important role”
Germany refused to vote on the recognition of Palestine.
According to Stephen Sabo, an expert on relations between the United States and Europe, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic path.
Deutsche Welle: In the beginning of the week, Germany first made it clear that it will vote against the Palestinians' request for the status of an observer at the United Nations.
But then Berlin refused to vote.
Why ?
Stephen Sabo: Germany does not support Israel’s actions in Gaza.
Now Germany needs to be cautious with regard to its special relations with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that it does not support the American position as well.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence, without being too critical to Israel.
During the Rebellion in Libya in March 2011, Germany also refused to vote on the introduction of a flight ban zone.
At the end, NATO made this proposal.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international matters?
Yes, it is so.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, i.e. passing from the policy that, so to say, was governed by the United States, to the German foreign policy itself.
Moreover, the situation is complicated by the lack of a concerted common policy for Europeans.
Thus, the Germans are again between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not accustomed to it.
I think they’re just realizing their role, but they’re on the way to a “more normal” foreign policy.
This is the foreign policy of France or the UK.
What does “normal” foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
This is the willingness to take a position in their national interests that does not depend on the position of the US or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, that is, on exports and connections with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
The economic interests of Germany differ significantly from the interests of other major states, and therefore Germany must defend its interests.
Did these economic interests affect the position in the Middle East conflict and the UN vote?
First, Germany has major sales markets in the Middle East, in the Gulf states.
Therefore, it needs to be cautious not to offend the public and the elites in Arab countries.
In any case, it plays its role.
But I’t give it too much importance, it’s not a completely unilateral connection.
But in any case, this plays an important role in the calculations of the Germans.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the United States by refusing to make important decisions, such as voting for Palestine?
I am confident that in Europe and even in the United States, the understanding of the German position prevails.
So I don’t think that was as dramatic as in the Libyan matter.
Maybe Germany will even gain some respect in this way.
After all, this signals that she should be taken seriously as a player on the international arena and that her interests should be considered.
There are different opinions about the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
The United States, on the contrary, clearly voted for the veto.
Is there any differences between the United States and many European countries?
Because of American domestic policy, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama government in the depth of heart has a sufficient understanding of the European position.
But in the context of the local political situation, the government of course cannot openly take such a position.
I believe that substantial differences in opinions are not as significant as usual.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, then notice that Obama is not enthusiastic about Netanyahu’s policy at all.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the United States on the one hand and the position of the most important partner in the EU on the other?
I think this is what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there was a unified, non-controversial European policy, but now it is not so.
Therefore, they cannot act within a wider approach and are forced to act instead, relying only on their own vision of the situation.
That’s what they do with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will take on a leading role in developing a common European position.
It’s clear that it’s not easy for Germany, at least because of its relations with Israel.
This topic has always been crazy.
But I think the Germans are clear that they should play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, will it not really take on its main role?
Is it hard to give Germany a leading role?
Germany has not yet used to it, it is always unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is always difficult to play a significant role.
Let’s consider, for example, the euro crisis – every time Germany takes on an important role, a variety of anti-German feelings are manifested.
The Germans do not just deal with it.
In fact, it’s a old problem: you don’t want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is much harder than the United States.
It should take into account the various neighbors and opinions, and this is not easy.
So, the influence of the United States in European policy is constantly weakening, but at the moment the EU does not fill this vacuum, who then remains?
The Germans have to play a bigger role.
Even if you don’t like it, it’s unpleasant, or it’s increasing unlove to you – that’s life!
Stephen Sabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, the institute in which academics and political experts from Europe and North America jointly investigate the problems of the transatlantic community.
In addition, Sabo is a member of the German Marshall Foundation, in which he specializes in German politics, U.S. foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
