Raffiscus is a forel, sweetened with salt and floating in the water up to a year, depending on what dust you need to.
As the darkness and the cold shrink, the crowd of Norwegians gather to a festival in Fagerne dedicated to this, let’s say, fascinating dish.
“They’re eaten raw and drunk with a rubber of aquavite, a local thin vodka,” explains Howard Halvarsen, a local firefighter in the profession and in the collaboration of the “Racfish General”, who leads the festival.
Everywhere around us people eat cut with small cubes of fish and drink it with large portions of alcohol.
“Someone likes aquavit more than rackfish,” Howard says.
This drink can break the smell.
I will try a couple of pieces.
If you’re able to carry a piece under your nose, then it’s not so bad – it’s little different from the portion of sushi that you’ve been on your bus for a long time.
Raffisk is a Norwegian product from a completely different time, times of poverty, when, before the appearance of the refrigerators, the fish in the autumn was mocked in hermetically closed bottles with salt water.
Then in the deep winter, when the fish was already well and thoroughly broken, it was extracted and, deepening the perception of alcohol, consumed in food.
Even in memory of the past generation is the fact that thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work and emigrate, mainly, to the United States.
Now the population is growing rapidly – more than 13% are immigrants, who are trapped here by jobs, high wages and a developed social security system.
The inhabitants of Sweden (a long rival, and not so long ago and a much more lively neighbor) massively come here to work.
Raffisk is perceived as some important symbol, an indispensable, though somewhat malicious element of the past of Norway.
This is one of the most expensive local dishes.
On the other hand, here is all expensive - a small glass of beer or sandwich will cost you 9 pounds (14 US dollars).
Norway rarely appears in world news, and most inhabitants of the country seem to be pleased with it.
People here still do not want to mention the name of Anders Breivik, a racist and right-wing extremist who shot down and killed 77 men, women and children last year.
Without mentioning his name, the terrorist attack is called "the 22th of July".
Norwegians are very difficult to believe that in their peaceful country one of their citizens has been capable of such brutality and murder.
The basis of today’s well-being in Norway is the growth (from the early 1970s) of one of the largest oil and gas industries in the world.
“But oil isn’t the only reason for our prosperity,” says Anna, our servant, whispering with a drawn rack, a woman with long, bright hair and surprisingly blue eyes, the embodiment of Nordic well-being.
We are such a people, as you call it, reasonable.
Like most Norwegians, she speaks well in English.
We don't like to show up, we're not praiseful.
Norway is very careful with its oil – the majority of the oil and gas industry’s revenue is invested in a special fund created for the benefit of future generations.
In the years prior to the global financial crisis, when everyone was shrinking with the money they didn’t have, Norway carefully counted all the costs.
“As long as you can ski in winter and walk in summer, this is enough for happiness,” says Anna.
“And there’s a rackfish,” she adds with a foolish laughter.
I’m standing in the snow in a row behind some food – a raffination with me is enough.
Here is a hamburger with salmon meat - it's exactly exotic, delicious juice meat.
But in the evening we are waiting for even more of the same fish with an unforgettable smell.
My hotel holds a special dining dedicated to rackfish, during which visitors by voting determine the best or the most aromatic fish.
There is a direct television show, in which they show the leading in a gallstoke-puppy, surrounded by plates with a raffin.
This is similar to the Eurovision Song Contest.
"So, Thor-Jurgen, what rating did you put for the best fish there in the mountains?"
“Yes, Howard, this is our assessment.”
Everyone laughs and praises.
Someone falls out of the chair, by taking over the aquavite.
Or maybe just breathing the smell of this fish.
