Bradley Manning did not complain of bad behavior, the accusation says.
The prosecutors are trying to deny Bradley Manning's statements about bad conditions of detention.
During the hearing, increased attention was paid to Maning’s stay in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defence requires the closure of the case on the grounds that the conditions of Maning’s imprisonment were cruel.
The U.S. Army is accused of theft of thousands of secret documents.
On Friday, the accusation tried to prove that the regular Bradley Manning, accused of the greatest escape of secret materials in U.S. history, did not take advantage of the many possibilities to complain about the misconduct he said had to be transferred while in military prison.
During a cross-interrogation at a pre-judicial hearing in Fort Mide, Maryland, military prosecutor Major Ashden Fein said that records of Maning's weekly visits by the prison administration for nine months of his detention in Quantico, Virginia, do not contain complaints of misconduct.
The preliminary investigation in the framework of the examination of the defensive request for the termination of the Manning case on the basis of the fact that the conditions of his detention were cruel and in itself were sufficient punishment, was carried out the next day after Manning said he intended to commit suicide while detained.
A military intelligence expert, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing several thousand secret documents during his service in Iraq.
This material was subsequently published on the WikiLeaks website.
WikiLeaks does not confirm that the source of information was Manning.
During the hearing on Friday, Prosecutor Fein and Manning reviewed the reports that were filled after Manning's visits by government representatives during his stay in Quantico prison, where he was under strict prison regimes from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, prison servants asked questions to Manning and recorded his answers.
When Prosecutor Fein asked on Friday about the reports, Manning acknowledged he assessed the treatment by the prison administration as "excellent" and the general conditions of imprisonment as "very professionally organized".
The reviewed reports do not contain any complaints of misconduct, despite the fact that Manning was directly asked about the conditions of his holding, Fein says.
Manning replied that he expressed oral concerns about these issues and that his visiting administration representatives discussed these issues with him and stated that they would deal with, but did not fix it in writing.
"They recorded 'problems are missing' (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn't mean I didn't raise this topic in the conversation," Manning says.
The military judge, Colonel Denis Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain of unlawful treatment with him in January 2011 during a committee meeting discussing suicidal intentions, which he expressed in writing a few months before.
Manning replied that during that meeting he wanted to get rid of the "traumatism warning" regime and relieve the conditions of imprisonment.
Representatives of the military leadership explained that the restricted prison regime - to a level lower than the supervisory regime to prevent suicide - was introduced to protect the prisoner, as well as for the security of others.
“I wanted to let the administration know that it’s okay with me, that they cancell the traumatic prevention regime... so that my level of life improves, from my point of view,” Manning explained.
On Thursday, Manning witnessed his arrest in Iraq and transferred to Kuwait, where he was held for two months before being transferred to prison at a naval base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He that his thoughts of suicide appeared in Kuwait, and that one day he lost consciousness due to a strong heat.
He explained that it is psychologically very difficult when you are not given to know how your destiny is resolved and what is happening in the outside world.
“My world was shrinking up to the Camp Ariffan base, up to the size of my prison,” Manning said on Thursday.
“I thought I would die in this cage.”
While in Quantico, Manning, according to him, spent most of his time in a small room - at least 21 hours, and often even more than 23 hours a day - in full loneliness.
Manning reports that he was allowed to leave only a mattress, a coat, a slope, a few items of clothes and glasses.
He says he was trying to move because sleeping or even just lying during the day was prohibited by the rules.
According to Maning, during his sleep, he was constantly in the eyes of a light penetrating outside the camera.
If the guards didn’t see his face when he turned into bed at night, then, according to him, he was awake and forced to turn back.
Manning's lawyer formally objected to Manning's unlawful treatment in January 2011.
In April 2011, Maninga was transferred to a military prison in Fort Livenworth, Kansas.
In addition, on Friday, the judge asked Manning about the statement he made during the testimony on Thursday, that after one night he was forced to sleep naked in his room in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked before the guards and other prisoners at the morning check.
Manning said he had no opportunity to cover the cover during the check.
Answering the question of the judge on Friday, Manning said he understood from the guard's order that he had to throw a cover that could be covered, but he admitted that no one had directly ordered him to throw it.
On Thursday, Manning said that the night before he was forced to sleep naked because he tried to show the officer that he was not a danger for himself.
Manning that he told the officer that he could use a strip of pants or pants to hurt himself, but he did not.
That night, according to Maning's testimony, his underwear, clothes and glasses were taken from the camera.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account what he had to experience during his imprisonment, and will significantly shorten the term of imprisonment in case Manning is declared guilty by a military court, which will begin his case at the beginning of the next year.
The Defence said it plans to propose to Manning to acknowledge guilt for less serious crimes, and other accusations to be disputed as excessive.
The renewal of the hearing is scheduled for this weekend, and the accused party is expected to insist that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon claims that Manning was held in Quantico in accordance with the rules that regulate the detention of the detainees with the strictest possible regime.
Among the accusations brought to Manning are the support of the opponent, the illegal promotion of the dissemination of data on the Internet, the transmission of information concerning national defence, and the theft of state property or documents.
If he is sentenced by all points of the accusation, he may be threatened to life imprisonment.
My crisis of national self-determination is a story of an American of Mexican origin.
According to the author, many Mexicans were forced to leave Mexico because of the lack of opportunities to realize themselves.
Mexicans tend to blame those who left because they remind residents of the country of difficult times.
Ruben Navarette believes that Mexicans of American origin break between two cultures.
During my recent trip to Mexico, I went through the corridors for arrivals, approached the border control zone and stopped on the spot.
The signs indicated two rows: one for Mexicanos (Mexicans), the second for Extranjeros (Strangers).
I stood before them for a few seconds without knowing where to go.
I grew up in Central California, and I was called a Mexican all my life.
It’s just a conditional name, like my friends in Boston call themselves Irish, and friends in New York call themselves Italian.
Later I stopped on the complex design of "American of Mexican origin".
But here I was in Mexico.
Here, in my grandfather's homeland, there was no need for conditional names or complex structures.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to ask questions or answer them.
But my vocabulary is poorer than the speakers, and I can’t get rid of American accent.
That’s why I got my American passport and got the turn for Extranjeros.
I remember this story a few days ago when the newly elected president of Mexico, Enrique Pena Nieto, visited the White House and met with President Obama.
On the agenda were common issues for the presidents of these countries: immigration, drugs and trade.
President Penya Nieto was pleased to talk about the rise of the Mexican economy, thanks to which the Mexicans will now, with the same success, be able to stay in Mexico instead of moving to the United States.
He wants to conclude a partnership agreement with the United States and Canada and to create a North American trade block like the European Union.
In addition, President Penya Nieto promised to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, but no specific proposals were made.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is a serious and fulfilled question of old harassment.
Most Americans never thought that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to give up half of their territory.
But the Mexicans think centuries, not minutes, and see reminders of those events in everything.
Therefore, it is only worth any U.S. official to be silent, even with a word of criticism towards Mexico, in the press and among the elites of the Mexican society, the complaints that the Americans violate the sovereignty of the neighbors are immediately spread.
And the descendants of Montesuma are filled with warfare.
Meanwhile, the most difficult is the relations of Mexico with more than 35 million Americans of Mexican origin living in the United States.
Do you want to talk about harassment?
They are enough.
In Mexico there are winners and losers, people who find opportunities in this country for themselves, and those for whom there are no such opportunities.
In Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver, or San Antonio so many people of Mexican origin only for one reason: at some point of their family history anyone — father or grandfather — had no opportunity to realize himself in Mexico and was forced to go to the north.
Most often, they were Mexicans of a certain type – dumb, poorly educated, from poor peasant families.
We are their descendants and we remember it.
In Mexico it is different.
Today our life is the realization of the American dream, we studied in good schools and prepared for good work, but we don’t forget that even this dream is American, not Mexican.
Our national self-determination is confused and unclear, but we know which country to consider its own.
the United States of America.
We also know that most representatives of the Mexican elite and the ruling class do not love us.
We answer them the same.
They see in us a reminder of humiliating defeats and treat us as people of second kind, as untrue Mexicans.
We don’t speak Spanish well enough, and our relations with Mexico are not strong enough.
Our existence itself is explained to them by failures.
If our ancestors had succeeded in Mexico, they would not leave.
We’t be now behind a silk curtain, finding a filled life in the United States, but losing spiritual connections.
My wife was born in Guadalajara and legally moved to the United States as a child, and this reminds me that there are certain trends between real Mexicans and Americans of Mexican origin: Mexicans understand their national identity more clearly, and Americans of Mexican origin it is offensive.
She is a citizen of the United States and believes she belongs to both countries.
At the same time, many of my well-known Americans of Mexican origin do not feel belonging to any of them.
We listen to the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but we love Bruce Springstine.
Having the best of the two worlds, you inevitably lose your roots.
In Mexico we are Americans.
In the United States, we are called Mexicans.
Now, as I discovered during my trip as if our relations were not confused enough, some Mexican leaders and intelligence representatives want to restore their relations with the diaspora.
They want the Americans of Mexican origin to work as a kind of ambassador to Mexico and represent its interests in the United States.
We could tell our American friends how beautiful it is and how nice it is to visit, and we could convince political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Ah of course.
Nothing will come out.
Too much harassment in the past.
And given the gap between the rich and the poor, the gap of corruption and drug trafficking, many of us don’t think this country is so beautiful at all.
Sorry, but deal with it yourself, Amigos.
And that is fair.
If a part of the Mexicans can still not forgive the United States as they did with Mexico a century and a half ago, they will have to accept the fact that some Americans of Mexican origin are still insulting for how they have recently been in Mexico with their relatives.
Yes yes.
Maybe we have more in common than I thought.
Old battles in the new Middle East
The ceasefire agreement between Israel and the Hamas could be a fragile foundation for further peace.
Is there a long-term peace between the Arabs and the Israelis in the Middle East?
Another round of bloodshed leads to the conclusion of the foolishness of such hopes.
It sounds usual, meaningless disputes about who first started; many buildings have become ruins; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed; for the first time during the conflict, missiles launched from the Gaza Strip fell near the capital of Israel Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
However, despite the fact that Israelis and Palestinians hopelessly engaged in their perpetual conflict, the Middle East has come to change.
This can be regarded differently, however, the events of the "Arab Spring" have surrounded in the rebellion storm many standing realities, and the Palestinians and the Israelis have failed to stay away from the storm that shocked the region.
Per, as a result, their struggle will be even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons that give hope for a way out of this deadly fool.
War Without the Winners
At first glance, the situation does not give reasons for optimism.
Even if the ceasefire, the agreement which was signed on 21 November, will be carried out, the clashes that occurred this week only strengthened the position of the forces on both sides.
The leaders of the Islamist movement Hamas, which came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, will declare that they forced Israel to withdraw despite the losses they suffered.
Despite the fact that some leaders of the group were destroyed and 1.7 million inhabitants were blocked in one of the most densely and problematic corners of our planet, Israel failed to destroy Hamas.
Indeed, Hamas is increasing its popularity on the West Bank of the Jordan River – another Palestinian territory now controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders can come to the conclusion that time works on them.
As the influence of Islamist movements increases in the Arab world, Hamas has new influential and wealthy friends.
The emerging regional leader, Turkey, which was once the closest ally of Israel among Muslim countries, supported Hamas, followed by Qatar, one of the richest and dynamically developing states in the Gulf.
Hamas celebrating supporters declare the creation around Israel of an Islamic Half Month – from Lebanon in the north, where Hezbollah is ruled, to Syria, where more and more Islamic rebels will throw down Bashar Assad’s power, and further to Jordan, where the king’s authorities are threatened by Hamas’ allies.
The most significant change in the balance of forces in the region occurred on the southern borders of Israel, in the most densely populated and important Arab country, in Egypt, where the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood movement was strengthened under President Mohammed Mursi.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was overturned in 2011, was a secular dictator who did not pay special attention to supporting Hamas.
Muslim brothers, on the contrary, are organizations much similar to Hamas, and their leaders are more inclined to populism.
In future diplomatic settlements, Hamas may become a significant player whose voice will not be able to silence even Israel and America.
At the same time, the supporters of the “hard” line in Israel will come to the opposite conclusions.
In the military sense, Hamas was overturned.
The Israeli anti-missile system “Iron Cup” justified the costs of its creation and successfully destroyed many of the launched Hamas missiles.
The citizens of Israel can sleep calmly, at least for a while.
As for diplomacy, the United States remained faithful to its unchanged position; many European countries also blamed the beginning of the last round of violence against Hamas.
Another important factor is the economic prosperity of Israel, especially with the government of Benjamin Netanyahu, who has greatly ignored the peace process.
Despite the fact that since 2004, about 30 Israelis have been killed by missiles launched from the Gaza Strip, Israel has managed to minimize the terrorist problem, partly by the wall that enters the West Bank of the Jordan River – a significant part of the unrecognized Palestinian State – and protects Jewish settlements that continue to expand despite the illegality of such actions from the point of view of international law.
The position of Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Lykud party – in the framework of preparation for the January 22 election – united with even more aggressive conservatives under the leadership of Avigdor Liberman, is very convenient.
What does it mean to encourage the Palestinians and give them their own state?
If they give all the power to their hands on the West Bank, will they not start launching missiles from there toward Israel, as their fellows in the Gaza Strip do?
It is better to keep them behind the wall and hardly suppress any attempts to raise the heads.
Per the supporters of the “hard” line will win; however, their calculations may be denied by the Arab Spring.
While Islamists who come to power in Egypt and other countries do not experience the warmest feelings towards Israel, their priority will be internal problems.
The defense part of the Israeli budget is greater than all its Arab neighbors, taken together.
A war with the regional superpower is unlikely to help the governments of the Arab countries strengthen their own economy.
The pragmatism of the Egyptian president, Mursi, who, together with Barack Obama, worked on a ceasefire, is a good sign and can mark the beginning of change.
Israel must at least take into account the long-term consequences of its policy.
As democratic changes arise in the Arab countries, the deprivation of the Palestinians of the right to self-determination is a slow-action bomb that will soon or later explode on Israeli occupied territories, like the bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression has already undermined the foundations of democratic order in the Jewish state, and the demographic aspect – the growth of the Arab population – only aggravates these problems.
For the bloody operations that are carried out every several years in the Gaza Strip to suppress the Hamas movement, the growing dissatisfaction of the international community has to be paid.
Both sides need external impulses.
The only solution remains to which healthier representatives from both sides and the majority of the rest of the world and our newspaper are constantly calling for: the formation of two states and the departure of territories by Israel in exchange for security.
There remains the hope, not too impressive in the short term, the hope that the ceasefire will allow other countries to influence the sides of the conflict more effectively.
Egypt, which has long been time to decide to stop the supply of weapons to the Gaza Strip, as well as Turkey and Qatar have, as never before, a favorable position to convince Hamas to recognize the borders of the Jewish state, adopted since 1967, taking into account the exchange of territories and the joint use of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries should also make efforts to reconcile the Hamas and Fatah movements.
This would do more for the creation of a Palestinian state than the upcoming UN vote, which could result in the recognition of the virtual state of Palestine.
His role in placing Israel at the negotiation table must be played by President Obama.
During his first term, he never presented his own plan for a peaceful settlement.
After returning to the White House, he continues to show no desire to connect to the solution of this problem.
This is a catastrophically unseen position.
The United States is very interested in stability in the Middle East.
This is possible only in the event of a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
In Australia, the unified packaging of cigarettes has come into force.
Warnings about the harm of smoking and the image of the diseases affected parts of the body are contrastly exposed on unclean green boxes, the same for all cigarette brands.
The first in world practice Australian law on single-type packaging of cigarettes and tobacco products came into force, replacing the logos and color designs of different brands with the same box of untouched olive color with junk images of diseases affected parts of the body and images of children whose health is undermined by the smoking of their parents.
In addition to different images and inscriptions warning of the harm of smoking, the only difference between the packages required from this Saturday is the names of the brands that are printed with the same small font.
These are the hardest conditions in the world for packaging of tobacco products.
The federal government of Australia says that the goal of this measure is to keep young people from smoking, depriving this bad habit of fashion status.
Research found that people who did not smoke before the age of 26, in 99 cases of 100 never become smokers.
“It is clear that even at the very young age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies are trying to bring through packaging,” the health minister Tanya Plibersek explains, referring to studies that showed that, for example, the crown in the logo is associated in children with the idea of a princess.
Australia is one of the countries with the lowest share of smokers in the world, so these changes will not affect the profits of transnational corporations, but the possibility of taking such measures is already being considered by other countries.
The tobacco industry has strongly opposed the adoption of this law.
Tobacco companies claim that this will only increase the share of the black market on which cheap and affordable cigarettes will be sold.
“This law will lead to serious consequences, different from those thought by its initiators,” says Scott McKintyre, a representative of British American Tobacco in Australia.
Manufacturers of fake products from China and Indonesia will supply much more such goods for sale in the streets of Australia.
For some, on the contrary, new laws contribute to the growth of the business.
Sandra Ha from a small family company, Zico Import Pty Ltd, claims that the demand for portsigarettes and silicone bottles that hide unpleasant images on the packaging has grown rapidly (practically from zero) since two months ago companies such as British American Tobacco, British Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost the case in the High Court of Australia where they tried to appeal this law.
According to Sandra Ha, Zico has already delivered about six thousand products to wholesale enterprises and awaits a new party.
It is a good business for us.
A potential obstacle to the effectiveness of such measures is, according to experts, the popularity of social networks among the population to which these measures are targeted.
After a number of laws adopted in Australia that made illegal television advertising tobacco and support them sports events, as well as prohibiting sellers from exhibiting cigarettes in a visible place, tobacco advertising moved to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned local companies and websites from placing advertising on the net, but it cannot restrict foreign websites.
“If you trade tobacco products and you have only this small shell, the idea of promoting your product on the internet will seem to be extremely attractive to you,” explains Beki Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman notes an increase in the number of reviews on trademarks written by the person of alleged ordinary users on social networks such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
The question arises: is it really a matter of the hands of a regular citizen who loves Marlboro cigarettes so much that he has not regretted his strength and time and made a video, or is it a advertising company behind it?
The Australian department of British American Tobacco says that the industry is now more busy adapting to new rules than advertising.
The representatives of the tobacco industry have even taken such measures as the sponsorship of Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules: these states make claims within the World Trade Organization, declaring that trade has been subjected to unfair restrictions, despite the fact that the trade relations of all of these countries with Australia are very small.
The WTO decision is expected by the middle of 2013.
According to Tani Plibersek, the government has discussed with other countries the possibility of adopting similar packaging laws.
In 2001, Canada introduced the first mandatory posting of photographs warning of smoking harm.
Now this rule is adopted in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
The possibility of strengthening laws is being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many smokers in Australia demonstratively do not obey the innovations.
These pictures don’t bother me.
I just don’t pay attention.
“You simply catch a cigarette and hide a pack in the pocket,” explains Victor El Hague, who purchases cigarettes with a picture of a tumor of the mouth on the pack.
To be honest, the only thing that can force me to leave is my little daughter.
James Yu, head of the King of the Pack tobacco store in the center of Sydney, claims that the same packaging complicated the task of placing goods on the roofs.
"Then I had an hour to discharge the new party, and now four hours," he complained.
“The government had to take and completely ban cigarettes, we would then say, what to do, okay, everything is over, we close the store,” he says, throwing his hands up.
To get bored in the world of electronic networks and constant connections is not so bad.
At this Thanksgiving Day I suddenly had to spend five hours at the airport because our plane had mechanical disorders and was replaced by another plane that we were waiting for.
