Every day, Anto descends to the bottom of the crater, where the serum gas rising from the depths of the Earth is frozen when it is in contact with the air.
Removing huge pieces of grape, the total weight of which can reach 70 kg, he puts them in two bamboo baskets, pulls the baskets on his shoulders and carries them up on a broken stone road.
To the top of the volcano, whose height is 2,386 meters, only 250 meters, however, wealthy carriers take more than 40 minutes to rise by a scalping step, hard to maintain balance and carefully searching the road so that they don’t fall down or fall from the break.
They know that one wrong step can cost them life, as it happened to a tourist from France who collapsed a few years ago from the Cavas-Ijena rocks.
Miners from Kavaj-Ijena earn 5 euro cents for each kilogram of grape they extract
When they get up, they put their way between the tourists who photograph them, as if they were circus monkeys and, tired of weighing heavy baskets, they walk three kilometers to the weights that the mining company placed a little above, at an altitude of 1,850 meters.
