Fabricio was 21 years old when he was announced that his AIDS analysis gave a positive result.
“I’m as if I’d been fooled,” he remembers that difficult, despite all the doctor’s touch, moment.
The boy hid this from his family.
Deciding to cope with the disease on his own, he wanted to learn about it as much as possible. And his efforts were justified - he already noted his 43th birthday.
Fabricio is one of the oldest HIV patients at the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), where he got in 1994, overcoming many obstacles.
He has been diagnosed with the "human immunodeficiency virus" (HIV) for 22 years. At the beginning of the 90s it would be difficult to believe - there were too few treatment options, too few knew about the disease, too predicted treated the patients.
So, even the director of the clinic of the Mexican Institute of Social Protection didn’t want to say goodbye to him, “because he had a cut.”
In other words, having AIDS at the time was a sentence.
Now it is possible to survive this syndrome and do so without deteriorating the quality of life.
Nevertheless, without knowing about their disease, many people still come when the virus has already damaged, "exhausted" their immune system and they suffer from opportunistic infections.
31 years after the emergence of AIDS in the world, at least after the first cases, “a great achievement at this point is that the survival of the patient who starts treatment in time and the survival of the general population are exactly the same,” said Hime Andrade Vilyanova, head of the HIV department of HCG, referring to the fact that this information was confirmed in April of this year in a prestigious scientific edition.
Infectionist and HIV/AIDS expert Andrade Villanueva explained that since 2008, scientists have come to the conclusion that AIDS is not a sentence, but the duration and quality of life depends on the degree of damage to the immune system in patients at the beginning of the diagnosis, with the best expected duration of life in those who do not use drugs: up to 30 years with the number of 200 CD4, and up to 50 years when 500 CD4 is.
Simply speaking, the above means that the person who is diagnosed with HIV-positive at the age of 25, according to these terms, “supporting control, will be able to live without problems up to 75 years,” he explained.
To evaluate this progress, it should be remembered that the length of life of Mexicans today is an average of 76 years.
Although mortality has decreased significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS has decreased from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (the annual UNEIDS report), it is also true that since the occurrence of AIDS, 60 percent of patients in the national database have died.
Only in Khalisco 255 people died in 2011, and 187 deaths have been recorded by May of this year; however, it is claimed that there has been universal access to antiretroviral drugs since 2005.
Why are there deadly outcomes?
I personally think the problem is not in access to treatment.
I think this is the case in our hospital.
At least in the last 12 years we have not had a deficiency in medications, the problem is that patients come very late because they don’t know about their infected state, i.e. in the late stages of the disease.
He brought devastating data: “Nine out of ten patients come when they already have any opportunistic infection; what should be done to have a greater impact on the overall mortality, so it is to make a diagnosis at a earlier stage, and therefore it is necessary to provide samples for mass detection, for all the people who will ask for it.”
In his proposal, experts and officials of the State AIDS prevention council in Halisco (COESIDA) agree, as well as the patients themselves, such as Fabricio, who went to a private laboratory for checking, motivated only by the fact that his friend did it and, despite his young age, he was already in the stage of AIDS and even suffered from the sarcoma of Caposhi, a cancer tumor that is one of the common complications.
Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they’re going to die and they don’t want to know anything.
“When I’m going to die anyway, it’s better that I’m going to swallow three times a week,” they say, but not in my case.
There are positive changes, I eat well, exercise, take medications.
Nowadays, his parents only know that he was suffering from cancer.
I live a normal life like any other.
"I work, I have a lot of jobs, I travel, I have an active sexual life, but with mutual responsibility, I take care of myself and the other person," said Fabricio, who agreed to share his personal life with MILENIO JALISCO to promote his statement to those who now, in the context of the World AIDS Day, are afraid.
Let them check if there was a risk of infection, let them know as soon as possible whether they are HIV-positive, so better, and if they already have a diagnosis, let them know that they can live like any other person, being responsible.
This report summarizes the topic of fighting AIDS this year.
Preservatives for the stick
The big gap between health programs and the ordinary citizen, believes Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who dealt with the HIV-related problem.
The most important is prevention.
In places dedicated to this task, "it has actually increased the spread of condoms, before we were given one or two, now we are given packs for a hundred, and that's very good, but it turns out that there are those who now still have no access to the condoms," he said.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
“Why are they you?” is a popular question, with evilness and condemnation, by social workers, school consultants, pharmaceutical workers and health workers who don’t want to hear teenagers.
I propose to change this ineffective distribution; that the preservatives are not only behind the stickers and that hundreds of them are in automates in public toilets in places that young people frequently visit.
This is not an incentive to dissolution.
It’s not about paying for beer and motel, Governor Emilio González replied when asked if it was possible to distribute condoms under his leadership.
“This is not sexuality, it’s best to make preservatives available to those who are already practicing sexual activity,” he said.
Key data in Halisco
In total, 13,435 cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV have been registered).
The state is ranked 4th in the national ranking for new and summary cases of AIDS and 13th for HIV.
92% of infections are related to the sexual path, 6% through the blood and 2% to the perinatal path.
According to estimates, 50,000 people can live with HIV, as for one registered case there are from 4 to 5 people who don’t know about it.
